  "text": "Kubernetes CNI (Container Network Interface) integration in v1.32.0 is implemented through a coordinated system spanning kubelet network management, pod sandbox creation, runtime interfaces, and CRI (Container Runtime Interface) specifications.\n\n## Core CNI Integration Components:\n\n### 1. Pod Creation and Network Setup Orchestration\nThe primary entry point is Kubelet.SyncPod (pkg/kubelet/kubelet.go), which calls kubeGenericRuntimeManager.SyncPod (pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/kuberuntime_manager.go). When a pod needs network setup, SyncPod calls createPodSandbox (pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/kuberuntime_sandbox.go) which initiates the CNI plugin invocation chain.\n\n### 2. Pod Sandbox Configuration and Network Namespace Setup\nThe createPodSandbox function (line 41 of kuberuntime_sandbox.go) calls generatePodSandboxConfig to build the PodSandboxConfig structure. This config includes:\n- Network namespace mode via runtimeutil.NamespacesForPod (pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/util/util.go, line 107)\n- NetworkNamespaceForPod (line 78) determines whether to use NODE or POD network namespace\n- DNS configuration via runtimeHelper.GetPodDNS (pkg/kubelet/kubelet_network.go, line 69)\n- Port mappings from container specs\n- Hostname and domain generation\n\n### 3. CNI Plugin Invocation\nThe generated PodSandboxConfig is passed to runtimeService.RunPodSandbox, which is defined in the CRI service interface (staging/src/k8s.io/cri-api/pkg/apis/services.go, line 72 in PodSandboxManager interface). The actual CNI plugin invocation happens in the container runtime shim (containerd, docker, cri-o) implementation, not directly in kubernetes/kubernetes. The kubelet delegates to the runtime via this CRI interface.\n\n### 4. IP Address Management (IPAM)\nAfter the pod sandbox is created, the IPAM process is handled by the CNI plugins themselves. The kubelet retrieves the assigned IP addresses via determinePodSandboxIPs (pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/kuberuntime_sandbox.go, line 313), which reads the Network field from PodSandboxStatus returned by the runtime. The pod status includes the IP address assigned by CNI plugins.\n\n### 5. Pod CIDR Management\nThe updatePodCIDR function (pkg/kubelet/kubelet_network.go, line 44) sends the cluster pod CIDR to the runtime via runtimeService.UpdatePodCIDR, allowing the runtime and CNI plugins to configure networking appropriately.\n\n### 6. Network-Related Status and Validation\nPodSandboxChanged (pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/util/util.go, line 28) validates that the network namespace mode matches and that the pod has received an IP address (line 59), which indicates successful IPAM configuration.\n\n### 7. Linux-Specific Network Utilities\nOn Linux systems, initNetworkUtil (pkg/kubelet/kubelet_network_linux.go, line 40) initializes iptables rules for Kubernetes networking, including KUBE-IPTABLES-HINT and KUBE-FIREWALL chains used by kube-proxy and CNI for packet filtering.\n\n## CRI API Definitions:\nThe CRI protocols are defined in:\n- PodSandboxManager interface (staging/src/k8s.io/cri-api/pkg/apis/services.go) - defines RunPodSandbox\n- RuntimeService interface (line 108) - composite service for all runtime operations\n- PodSandboxConfig structure (staging/src/k8s.io/cri-api/pkg/apis/runtime/v1/api.pb.go, line 1419) - contains NetworkConfig and NamespaceOption\n- NamespaceOption structure (line 895) - specifies network namespace mode (NODE or POD)\n- NetworkConfig structure (line 7649) - carries network configuration details\n\n## Runtime Interfaces:\nThe kubelet abstracts container runtime operations through:\n- Runtime interface (pkg/kubelet/container/runtime.go, line 71) - includes UpdatePodCIDR method (line 124)\n- RuntimeHelper interface (pkg/kubelet/container/helpers.go, line 48) - includes GetPodDNS and GeneratePodHostNameAndDomain\n\n## Network Plugin Manager Coordination:\nThe kubeGenericRuntimeManager (pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/kuberuntime_manager.go) acts as the network plugin manager, coordinating all CNI-related calls during pod lifecycle:\n1. Creates pod sandbox with network configuration\n2. Waits for CNI to assign IPs (via PodSandboxStatus retrieval)\n3. Updates pod status with assigned IPs\n4. Handles pod deletion which triggers CNI teardown\n5. Manages CIDR updates to CNI plugins\n\nThe entire flow ensures that CNI plugins are properly invoked with correct network configuration, IPAM is completed before containers start, and network resources are cleaned up during pod termination."
}

